INSERT INTO `pas_talks` VALUES (1,'QAI','Quality Assurance Institute','Conference on Regaining Business Confidence in Information Technology','Orlando, FL','Keynote Address','1999-04-14','Insurance Coverage: The New Driver for Quality','','The year 2000 compliance issue is challenging and \r\nwill continue to test many organizations even beyond the first day \r\nof the new millennium. This presentation will address the subject \r\nof insurance coverage for organizations and how it impacts quality, \r\nnot only in view of the year 2000 concern, but also beyond that \r\nissue. Insurance companies are becoming increasingly concerned \r\nabout all aspects of the way those who are insured by them conduct \r\nbusiness from quality to liability exposure and potential litigation.'),(34,'','Lockheed Martin Information Services','','Orlando, FL','Opening Keynote','2001-02-06','The Value of Information Technology Services','','The worth of I.T. services can be judged only in the context of the financial performance of the entire enterprise.  The first part of the presentation will show comparisons between Lockheed-Martin and look-alike firms,such as Boeing, TRW and others.  The analysis will show that the central focus of I.T. services in L-M  should concentrate on reducing the Cost of Goods, which include the\r\ncosts of Purchases and Administration expenses.<p>\r\n\r\nSince the primary value of I.T. services can be found in improving organizational effectiveness, the potential gains from further integration with the supply value-chain will be highlighted as the most likely top priority objective for L-M.<p>\r\n\r\nThe discussion about I.T. services efficiency gains will dwell on the measurement of Information Productivity as the entire enterprise and how I.T. can identify the most rewarding investment opportunities.<p>\r\n\r\nThe presentation will conclude with observations about benchmarking I.T. spending, especially in comparison with prices quoted by outsourcers.  Emphasis will be placed on the re-allocation of I.T. spending from ongoing operations and maintenance expenses to funds that need to become available for making innovative investments.'),(2,'FRB','Federal Reserve System','Private Briefing to the Board of Governors','Washington, DC','Private Briefing','1999-04-15','Is There a Computer Paradox?','<a href=\"http://www.strassmann.com/pubs/frb-041599.pdf\">Complete \r\npresentation</a> <font size=-1>(Adobe Acrobat, 924Kb)</font><br>\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/library/tech/99/04/biztech/articles/14tech.html\">New York Times article</a> describing briefing <font size=-1>(Page 1, 14-Apr-1999)</font>','Assessment of the Information Productivity of U.S. industrial \r\ncorporations.<br>\r\nEffects of information technologies on the productivity \r\nof the U.S. information workforce.'),(3,'IOCEO','International Organization of CEOs','Private Briefing to the TEC III Executive Committee','New York, NY','Private Briefing','1999-04-16','How to Assess a Firm\'s Knowledge Capital','','Mr. Strassmann owns the Knowledge Capital U.S. Registered \r        Trademark, a technique for calculating a firm\'s knowledge capital \r        from available financial disclosure data. To illustrate the analytic \r        methods and how to apply them in planning and budgeting, Mr. Strassmann \r        will use public data from named members of the CEO organization.  Comparisons will \r        be made against the \"book value\" of the firms as well as stock market valuations. \r        As a special feature of this analysis Mr. Strassmann will evaluate the \r        contributions of these firm\'s information technology to their Knowledge Capital.'),(4,'MISM','MIS Magazine','Mindshare Conference','Leura, Australia','Workshop','1999-05-10','Measuring the Return-On-Investment From I.T. Projects','','(May 10-11) Seminar includes Assessment of Information Productivity, I.T. \r        expense benchmarking and Knowledge Capital evaluation.'),(5,'IIR','Institute for International Research','Conference on Information Technology Performance Management','Chicago, IL','Keynote Address','1999-05-24','Measuring and Evaluating the Productivity of Corporate Information Management','','The line items reported by U.S. industrial corporations as \r        Sales, General, Administrative and Research & Development offer the \r        most reliable public estimates of what it costs to manage and coordinate \r        a business internally as well as to communicate with suppliers and customers.  \r        This expense, conventionally identified as \"overhead,\" is as good a \r        representation of the costs of information management as is available.  \r        It includes not only the payroll for the people engaged in information \r        tasks but also expenses for advertising, promotion, consultants and \r        information technology.<p> \r        An examination of how the costs of information management relate to \r        all other costs of doing business offer valuable insights for a Chief \r        Information Executive who aspires to be more than just a Chief Computer \r        Executive. Mr. Strassmann will describe how over the last ten years \r        the U.S. industrial corporations:\r	<ul>\r	<li> Lowered the costs of information management required to deliver goods and services to customers\r	<li> Increased per employee information management costs faster than employee compensation\r	<li> Lowered information management costs in support of revenues;\r	<li> Lowered the ratio of information management costs to operating profits;\r	<li> Lowered the ratio of information management costs to net assets in place\r	<li> Information Productivity has improved since 1991.\r	</ul>\r\r	While these changes were taking place the U.S. industrial corporations \r	also showed the following characteristics:\r	<ul>\r	<li> Ninety-two percent of firms incurred higher expenses for information \r	management than for the costs of ownership of their net capital assets. \r	This makes the utility of asset-based productivity ratios (such as ROA, \r	ROI or ROE) questionable as a measure of performance;\r	<li> Only fifty-eight percent of firms delivered a positive economic \r	value-added (EVA). This makes accounting profits questionable as a \r	measure of operating results\r	</ul>\r	Mr. Strassmann will show how Economic Value-Added (EVA) and Information \r	Productivity ratios should be used in assessing a firm\'s effectiveness \r	in use of information resources.  Emphasis will be placed on specific \r	planning and financial budgeting methods.'),(6,'Java99','Sun Microsystems','JavaOne Conference','San Francisco, CA','Keynote Address','1999-06-14','Analyzing Information Technology Budgets as a Long-Term Investment, Not as a Current Expense.','<a href=\"http://www.strassmann.com/pubs/art-of-roi/\">Streaming video &amp; slides</a>','Financial techniques and methods of investment justification, using the \r\nlanguage of financial analysts and investment review committees of corporations, \r\nnot in technical terms.'),(7,'CB','Conference Board','Meeting on Delivering Results in the Global Marketplace','New York, NY','Plenary Address','1999-06-15','Risk Management: The Need for a Shared View Among the \r        I.T. and the Operating Executives','','Fifty-six percent of the US workforce is employed \r        in information occupations and about eighty percent of \r        this workforce depends on computers to function effectively. \r        In the face of this accelerating dependency, IT projects often \r        fail from the inability to properly plan for risk and to clearly \r        communicate those risks, and their associated benefits, to the \r        executive level. Every executive must now become fluent in assessing \r        and dealing with the potential risks from the failure of their \r        information initiatives since failure penalties often exceed the \r        cost of information technologies. Risk management, as a means \r        for allocating scarce resources, has become at least as important \r        as the purely technological issues which up to now have been the \r        primary focus of dialogues between general managers and computer experts.'),(8,'BSG','BrainStorm Group','SMARTsourcing Conference','San Francisco, CA','Opening Keynote Address','1999-06-28','Smartsourcing for Innovation','<a href=\"http://www.strassmann.com/pubs/smartsourcing/slides.pdf\">Slides</a> \r        <font size=-1>(Adobe Acrobat, 1.3Mb)</font>','The old forms of outsourcing, e.g. taking over a customer\'s\r         costly, obsolete and labor intensive information\r          systems can be characterized as \"junkyard\" operations. <p>\r\r	The rapidly emerging new demands for systems innovations will rely\r	on Internet-based architectures that keep \"client\" and local\r	\"server\" assets to the barest minimum and will offer centralized\r	utilities consisting largely of\r 	data repositories and application processing \"farms\".<p>\r\r	Successful outsourcing arrangements will become the \r	means for an organization to achieve cost reductions and\r	competitive improvements through <b>innovation</b>, <i>not</i> through\r	custodianship of technologically obsolete assets.<p>\r\r	Junkyard outsourcing will not be profitable because it will \r	be stuck with the risks and costs for unwinding \r	obsolete services and declining number of transactions.<p>\r\r	Profits (and value-priced operations) will be made in\r	those smartsourcing contracts where the outsourcers\r	who can offer large savings and superior  new\r	competitive capabilities.  This requires shift to vastly more efficient\r	architectures that are not fat client/fat server centric, but\r	thin client/wide band/central utility focused.<p>\r\r	In due course the competition between the junkyard and the smartsourcing\r	architectures will be resolved in favor of network centric\r	(the network is the computer) solutions.<p>\r\r	Strassmann will emphasize that if an outsourcing strategy \r	concentrates on  short-term cost reductions\r	for existing systems assets, everybody will be a loser.\r	The customers for outsourcing will lock themselves into\r	long term commitments which will increasingly become\r	economic liabilities.<p>\r\r	Therefore, operating cost reductions as the primary criteria for \r	entering into smartsourcing relationships, will increasingly\r	lead everyone down a destructive\r	path.  Viewing smartsourcing as an engine for building\r	\"knowledge capital\" through innovation then becomes by\r	far the most reliable metric for judging the merits\r	of smartsourcing initiatives.'),(9,'UVa','Center for the Management of Information Technology','University of Virginia','Charlottesville, VA','Executive Briefing','1999-07-16','Is There a Computer Paradox?','','Mr. Strassmann will present detailed evidence, based on a study\r\nof 1,560 US industrial corporations, that there is no proof (as yet)\r\nthat computers have improved the productivity of corporate information management.'),(10,'Delphi','The Delphi Group','International Knowledge Management Executive Summit - IKMS\'99','Washington, DC','Keynote','1999-10-06','How Much Knowledge Capital Do You Possess?','<a href=\"http://www.delphigroup.com/kms/ikms-overview.htm\">Details and Registration</a>','The talk will present the results of studies\r	of 1,560 US industrial corporations and 542 US banks.\r	It will show original research findings from Strassmann\'s forthcoming book\r	(Spring 2000), including:\r	<ol>\r	<li>Comparisons of Financial Capital with Knowledge Capital for the 2,102 firms.\r	<li>Comparisons of Stock Market Valuation with Knowledge Capital for the 2,102 firms.\r	<li>Knowledge Capital per Employee for the 2,102 firms.\r	<li>Recent Knowledge Capital trends and how they relate to productivity and interest rates.\r	</ol>'),(11,'brkm','','Brazilian National Conference on Knowledge Management','Rio de Janeiro, Brazil','Keynote Address','1999-10-18','Measuring Knowledge Capital','',''),(12,'IFPUG','International Function Point Users Group','Annual conference: New Millenium, New Metrics','New Orleans, LA','Opening Keynote Address','1999-10-20','Measuring Knowledge Capital - The Ultimate Metrics Challenge','','Overhelming evidence shows that conventional financial reports do not report \ror measure the most important corporate asset which is Knowledge Capital. The current \rstock market valuations also place large premiums on what is represented by firms\ras \"intellectual capital.\"<p>\r\rStrassmann\'s lecture will show how one can assess what is the dollar \rvalue of Knowledge Capital and explain how to estimate the worth of\r\"intellectual capital.\"<p>\r\rThe lecture will discuss the reasons for the many inconsistencies\rin the current valuations of information resources.\rA critique of present budgeting and planning practices\rwill describe how excessive concentration on budgeting\rknowledge acquisition as a current expense and not as a\rlong-term investment leads to waste of this valuable asset.<p>\r\rKnowledge Capital metrics offer practical insights how\rto evaluate and justify investments in a firm\'s\rinformation infrastructure, in improved life-cycle costing\rof software and in designing reliable databases. The\rprincipal tool for making such assessments is the\rconcept of \"knowledge accumulation inefficiency\" which\rreveals the rate at which a firm may be squandering its most valuable\rinformation assets.'),(13,'ICMG','International Communications for Management Group','World IT Congress - Asia Pacific','Sydney, Australia','Opening Keynote Address','1999-11-05','Planning and Budgeting Practices to Assure the Realization of IT Benefits','','Throughout his career Paul Strassmann has challenged \r        thinking on the relation between information technology and the \r        profitability of companies.  At the Congress his thought-provoking \r        presentation will address the topic of:\r	<blockquote>\r	\"Even superior execution cannot compensate for an inferior choice what to \r	do. Whether IT investments contribute to increased economic value-added \r	is largely determined when plans set forth goals and objectives and when \r	budgets allocate funds, missions and schedules for implementation. \r	Planning and budgeting are the only time when top management can make \r	sure that IT is \"aligned\" with the goals of a firm. During planning \r	and budgeting the risk destiny of IT is pre-set in that it sets in \r	place the risk. expectations, performance measures, schedules and \r	major technology choices. After all of these decisions are largely \r	locked in, the IT organization is not left with too many choices \r	except how to execute the plans the best way they know how.<p>\r	It will be the central theme of Mr Strassmann\'s presentation that \r	IT executives do not devote sufficient time to the planning and \r	budgeting process because they are always rushed to proceed with \r	installation and delivery of systems. Such haste is in most cases \r	the single greatest source of all IT fatalities.\"\r</blockquote>'),(14,'pskm','PeopleSoft Corporation','','Canberra, Australia','Seminar and Briefing','1999-11-09','Measuring Knowledge Capital','',''),(15,'sing','Strategic Consulting','','Singapore','Seminar','1999-11-12','Justification of Expenditures for Information Technologies','','November 11-12'),(16,'sing1','','CNBC Morning Show','Singapore','TV Panel','1999-11-12','Information Technology Payoffs','',''),(17,'va','','Commonwealth of Virginia Conference','McLean, VA','Keynote','1999-12-07','Shifting to Business Process Services - The Unintended Consequences of the Y2K Mess','',''),(18,'cnbc','','CNBC Morning Show','Cable','TV Panel','2000-01-03','The Y2K Hoax','',''),(19,'lehrer','','The Lehrer Report','TV','TV Panel','2000-01-05','The Y2K Profligacy','<font size=-1><a href=\"http://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/cyberspace/jan-june00/y2k_1-5.html\">transcript\r        </a> | <a href=\"http://audio.pbs.org:8080/ramgen/newshour/january00/y2k_1-5.rm?altplay=y2k_1-5.rm\">RealAudio</a></font>',''),(20,'wb1','The World Bank','','Washington, DC','Keynote','2000-03-29','Information Economics - The Key to I.I. Planning and Budgeting','',''),(21,'vanguard','The Vanguard Group','','Washington, DC','Keynote','2000-05-06','Creating Economic Value Through Information Productivity','',''),(22,'butler','The Butler Group','A Paul Strassmann Master Class','The Swallow International Hotel, Cromwell Road, London, UK','Seminar','2000-05-16','Assessment of Productivity of Information Resources','Agenda and Registration: <a href=\"http://www.ButlerGroup.com/pstrassmann/event.htm\">HTML</a> or\r<a href=\"http://www.strassmann.com/pubs/bg/ip-masterclass.pdf\">PDF</a> ','A rare opportunity to hear Paul Strassmann explain the concepts of Information \rProductivity and his methods for measuring Knowledge Capital.<p>\r\rThis one-day seminar will combine Master Class and workshop activities to challenge and enlighten.\rA welcome speech will be given by Martin Butler, Chairman of Butler Group.\rJonathan Stephenson, Information Productivity Consultant, will deliver the keynote speech and introduction.\rPaul Strassmann will explain his ideas for measuring the effectiveness of organisations. His talk will cover:\r<ul>\r<li>The importance of having metrics that reflect the information-driven model of modern business.\r<li>How to calculate Information Productivity.\r<li>How to make meaningful comparisons of IT spending between look-alike companies.\r<li>Knowledge Capital, its importance and measurement.\r<li>Accounting for IT spending.\r</ul>\rAfter lunch, you will have the opportunity to work with Paul Strassmann and Martin Butler in a more intimate,\rworkshop environment.'),(23,'apqc','American Productivity &amp; Quality Center','','Houston, TX','Keynote','2000-05-26','The Valuation of Knowledge Capital','',''),(24,'aec','','Army Executive Conference','Arden House','Seminar','2000-06-04','Information Threats and Their Consequences for U.S. National Security Policy','',''),(25,'infowar','','Infowar Conference','Washington, DC','Keynote','2000-11-12','The Economics of Information Security, Extortion, Ransom and Arson','<A href=\"http://www.strassmann.com/pubs/infowar.pdf\">Slides</a> <font size=-1>(1.3Mb)</font>, \r        <A href=\"http://www.misti.com/conference_show.asp?id=IW00&type=Session&workID=09%2F12%2F2000#1351\">Details and Registration</a>','Information security is expensive--counted in trillions of dollars worldwide.\r                              For decision-makers weighing the need for infosecurity against its cost, the real\r                              challenge is determining how much  money to spend and when to deploy it to\r                              effectively balance expenses and risks. In this authoritative session you will\r                              discover how  the time-tested principles of risk management, as developed by\r                              the insurance industry, offer the best economic cost/benefit models for\r                              allocating funds for information security. You will find out why, in the case of\r                              individual organizations,  insurance practices that dictate the adoption of  codes,\r                              standards, independent inspection, risk-pooling and reinsurance can also apply\r                              to information warfare situations. You will find out why policy makers should\r                              examine actuarial practices and formal risk engineering as cost-containment\r                              measures. You will also review examples of extortion, ransom, and arson\r                              insurance policies that will illustrate practices that can be used when handling\r                              information warfare exposures.'),(26,'vit2000','','The Verisign Internet Trust Symposium','The Fairmont, San Jose, CA','Keynote','2000-10-05','Protection of Knowledge Capital: How Much is it Worth?','','Spending money on Information Security is comparable to purchasing an \r insurance policy.Ê For an estimate of how much safety to buy a risk manager \r must start with an assessment of the dollar value of losses one must prevent.\r Mr. Strassmann will suggest that estimating the worth of a firm\'s \"Knowledge \r Capital\" should be the preferable method for arriving at the size of \r vulnerable information-related assets.Ê He will show how to make such \r valuation calculations and how to apply them in explaining expenditures for \r information protection.Ê The presentation will include illustrative examples \r of key metrics, such as the valuation of \"Knowledge Capital\" per employee \r and the ratio of Financial to Knowledge Assets.'),(27,'efast2000','ICM','European Forum on Advanced Strategies and Technology','Barcelona, Spain','Keynote','2000-11-07','Where are the Profits from E-Commerce?','<A href=\"http://www.fasteceurope.com/html/intro.htm\">Details and Registration</a>',''),(28,'witc2000','','World I.T. Congress','M.S. Marco Polo, Barcelona, Spain','Keynote','2000-11-10','The Economic Structure of E-Commerce','<A href=\"http://www.worldit-europe.com\">Details and Registration</a>',' Business-to-business e-commerce is the next great opportunity for expanding \r\n the influence of IT people. Terms such as \"value-chain streamlining\" and \r\n \"eliminating work-flow processes\" have crept into the vocabulary of IT \r\n executives, as corporate Boards push their IT shops to proceed with yet nother \r\n round of huge investments.<p>\r\n\r\n Whenever predictions of huge savings call for large expenditures, IT \r\n executives may boost their standing by offering verifiable evidence as to where the \r\n profits may end up.<p>\r\n\r\n Mr. Strassmann has examined the cost structure of more than 10,000 \r\n industrial suppliers.  Since suppliers of finished goods, in turn, depend on \r\n other suppliers, he was able to construct a financial model of the \r\n costs of the entire supply pipeline, usually involving up to four major\r\n layers of intermediaries. It offers an explanation of where the money is \r\n spent. At each layer of supply a firm adds to its costs information expenses for \r\n sales, marketing, administration, research and development, and IT. These \r\n costs, averaging 16% are included in the manufacturer\'s sales price, thus \r\n taking out a big chunk out of the manufacturer\'s value added.  When\r\n each manufacturers\' information costs are added up they may amount\r\n to anywhere from 25% to 45% of a product’s wholesale price.<p> \r\n\r\n Thus cost reduction in information management across the entire \r\n supply pipeline becomes the largest opportunity for boosting profits. \r\n Mr. Strassmann will show examples how the analysis total information management\r\n across all of the layers of supply value chain is necessary before \r\n justifying an e-commerce project. The greatest benefits will be realized \r\n only by those who will have the market power to extract value chain savings \r\n and then retain them as profits.'),(29,'witc2000a','','World I.T. Congress','Barcelona, Spain','Seminar & Tutorial','2000-11-12','Assessment of Information Productivity of Corporations','<A href=\"http://www.worldit-europe.com\">Details and Registration</a>',''),(30,'','Butler Group','Executive Briefing','Four Seasons Hotel, London','Executive Briefing','2000-11-14','The Economics and Futures of Business to Business E-Commerce','','Business-to-business and business-to-consumer E-commerce systems are the \r next great opportunities for making profitable IT investments.Ê As IT \r spending flows into transforming existing software into Internet-based \r E-commerce services it becomes imperative to figure out who will benefit and \r how much profit will be realized from these technologies.Ê Whenever \r predictions of huge savings call for multi-million funding it may enhance \r the career of an IT executive to show where the gains can be found after \r E-commerce schemes become operational.<p> \r Strassmann has examined the financial records of more than 10,000 industrial \r suppliers and has analyzed their cost structure.Ê Since suppliers of \r finished goods also depend on other suppliers, he was able to construct a \r financial model of the entire multi-stage supply pipeline. This model offers \r an explanation of where the money is presently spent and what costs become \r displaceable by E-commerce.Ê He will also show how the rising economic power \r of global business-to-business purchasing consortia is likely to end up \r dominating the pricing of E-commerce transactions when the elimination of \r weak competitors takes place.<p>\r The presentation will explain how an IT executive should analyze E-commerce \r opportunities. It will demonstrate that, on the average, 35% of revenue now \r embedded in the entire supply pipeline becomes eligible for displacement by \r means of E-commerce. The entire presentation will focus on the total \r information content, as a share of the final price of a purchased item. A \r special examination will also focus on the potential retail savings in \r business-to-consumer sales.<p>\r A partial preview of the topics that will be covered in this presentation \r can be found <A HREF=\"http://www.strassmann.com/pubs/cw/netprofits.shtml\">here</a>.'),(31,'influ2000','','Influent InfoProducer Conference','Lake Buena Vista, FL','Keynote','2000-12-04','Documents, Knowledge Capital and Information Systems','<A HREF=\"http://www.influent.com/infoproducer/\">Details and Registration</a>',' The study of the written word offers one of the most insightful ways of \r understanding all human progress.Ê All wealth is the result of accumulation \r of capital, first in the form of land, then in the form of financial assets \r and now in the form of knowledge.Ê In the historical evolution of the human \r species the changes in the delivery of recorded information - in the form of \r documents - has always marked the beginning of a new phase in social \r advancement.<p> \r Mr. Strassmann will illustrate the results of his work on the dominant role \r of Knowledge Capital in the global economy.Ê Based on his work as the \r originator and organizer of the Xerox Exhibition on the History of the \r Written Word he will show how technological changes have always resulted in \r the shifts in economic power in favor of those who could control the \r creation and distribution of recorded knowledge.<P>\r With the explosive growth of the global Web we are now witnessing an \r unprecedented disruption in existing relationships.Ê Mr. Strassmann will \r discuss what are the consequences of the Web now containing an estimated 550 \r billion documents.Ê Everyone can now enter the document publishing business \r as the systems costs of creation and distribution approach zero.Ê The \r industrial-age emphasis on reducing the costs of making documents will now \r be displaced by systems that will enhance that capacity of individuals to \r comprehend the contents.'),(32,'influ2001','Influent','Executive Summit for IT Service & Support','Scottsdale, AZ','Keynote','2001-01-29','What are your Employees Worth?','<A HREF=\"http://www.influent.com/itss2001\">Details and Registration</a>',' All great ideas must ultimately be subject to the test of economic \r\n viability.Ê Much of the prevailing rhetoric about \"intellectual capital\", \r\n \"knowledge economy\" and \"employees-as-our-most-important-asset\" appears to \r\n be more attractive when preached from the lectern as compared with the \r\n difficulties in defending spending proposals during budget reviews.  <p>\r\n Paul Strassmann\'s approach to Knowledge Capital applies the disciplines of \r\n financial analysis to calculate, in ways that are verifiable and \r\n reproducible, the worth of corporate assets which at present are aggregated \r\n as non-quantifiable attributes of Quality, Corporate Culture, Customer \r\n Franchise, Organizational Capabilities and the widely fluctuating \r\n differences between stock market and accounting valuations of corporations.<P>\r\n This keynote will cover the following topics: \r\n  <li>1. The Economic Structure of U.S. corporations\r\n  <li>2. Problems with Accounting and Stock Market Valuations\r\n Ê<li>3. How to quantify a firm\'s Knowledge Capital (with illustrative examples)\r\n Ê<li>4. How to attribute Knowledge Capital to Employees and how to evaluate \r\n employee compensation if they are evaluated as an \"asset\".Ê Each of these \r\n topics will be illustrated by examples of calculations for named firms.'),(33,'','Chamber of Commerce, New Canaan','The Roger Sherman','New Canaan, CT','Luncheon Talk','2001-01-24','Merchants, The Web and E-Commerce','','Features statistics about the penetration of E-commerce in retail sales, the availability of on-line shopping options and a description of new technologies for enhancing the consumer\'s shopping experience.'),(35,'','GIGA','GigaWorld I.T. Forum 2000','Las Vegas, NV','Keynote','2001-05-21','Measures of I.T. Leadership','<a href=\"http://www.gigaworldus.com/Gigaworld-US/keynotes4.asp\">More info</a>','One way of defining what is the elusive concept\r\nof \"leadership\" is by showing how one would\r\nevaluate it.  There are are a number of \r\npopular methods for ranking leadership excellence.\r\nThese  may lead to unexpected results and Strassmann \r\nwill show why this is so.<p>\r\n\r\nTo define leadership in measurable terms\r\nStrassmann will base his observations on\r\nresearch that has shown that\r\nmaking strategic choices and competitive\r\nassessments account for most of the financial\r\nresults.  A distinction will be made between \r\n\"management\" which\r\nis concerned with operational effectiveness\r\nand \"leadership\" which involves making tradeoffs\r\nbetween risky and often conflicting \r\nchoices.  The presentation will include\r\nan illustrative case and demonstrate\r\nwhat an I.T. executive ought to do\r\nin order to align investments in I.T. projects\r\nwith corporate strategies and goals.'),(36,'','C4E - Centro de Eficiência, Eficácia e Estratégia Empresarial','Sheraton Hotel','Lisbon, Portugal','Seminar and Workshop','2001-05-29','Information Management Governance and Productivity Assessment','','<li>Session 1<br>\r\nInformation Management Governance:<P>\r\n\r\nStrassmann uses the word \"governance,\" but he really wants to talk about \"organizational politics.\" He distinguishes between information management and information technology.  This lecture will center on a view that the optimal organization is a federation. In a federation, power is balanced between a central unit and a number of constituent units.  Strassmann uses the constitutional model to develop a seven-layer information constitution. The top layer is global and includes all functions that deal with the outside; the bottom layer is personal and includes all data that people want to keep private.<P>\r\n\r\n<li>Session 2<br>\r\nInformation Productivity:<P>\r\n\r\nThe primary objective of this presentation is to demonstrate that conventional measures of corporate productivity, such as Return on Assets (ROA) or Return on Investment (ROI) overlook the dominance of information management expenditures in the determination of financial results.  Strassmann will outline a 15-step process for analyzing the effectiveness of managerial, administrative, marketing and all other information-handling personnel.  In this context information technologies are seen as enablers of human productivity and not as investments that explain productivity gains.<P>\r\n\r\n<li>Information Technology:<p>\r\n\r\nThis session will explain how one can answer the question whether information technology expenditures are inadequate or excessive.  Techniques for making comparisons with spending by competitors (e.g. competitive benchmarking) will be emphasized and illustrated.<P>\r\n<li>\r\nKnowledge Capital:<P>\r\n<li>\r\nInformation management constitutes both a primary cost and the most valuable asset of corporations in the new economy.  However, traditional accounting practices offer no consistent method for incorporating a measure of this vital ingredient.  Strassmann has formulated a set of metrics to surmount this shortcoming and to permit executives, information managers, and investors to make informed decisions and project into the future likely consequences of past performance.  Knowledge Capital provides an operational means for comparing the economic health of corporations from routinely reported financial data.<P>\r\n\r\n<li>Session 3<br>\r\nThe Economics and the Future of Business-to-Business E-Commerce:<br>\r\n\r\nStrassmann has examined the financial records of more than 10,000 industrial suppliers and has analyzed their cost structure.  Since suppliers of finished goods also depend on other suppliers, he was able to construct a financial model of the entire multi-stage supply pipeline.  He will also show how the rising economic power of global business-to-business purchasing consortia is likely to end up dominating the pricing of E-commerce transactions when the elimination of weak competitors takes place.  The presentation will explain how an IT executive should analyze E-commerce opportunities. '),(37,'','','','','Briefing','1999-01-21','The Politics of Information Management','',''),(38,'','','','','Briefing','1999-02-05','Operating Government as a Business','',''),(39,'','','','','Briefing','1999-02-18','Independent Verification and Validation of Year 2000 Systems Risks','',''),(40,'','','','','Briefing','1999-03-03','Terrorism - the Ultimate Infrastructure Protection Challenge','',''),(41,'','','','','Briefing','1999-04-12','Software Risks: The Keys 