0-03-09','The Valuation of Knowledge Capital on the Web','',''),(63,'','','','','Briefing','2000-05-08','Creating Economic Value through Information Productivity','',''),(64,'','','','','Briefing','2000-09-16','A Special U.S. Army Airforce Mission in World War II','',''),(65,'','','','','Briefing','2000-11-28','The Economics of Distributed Image Databases','',''),(66,'','University of Virginia','Satellite video conference','','Seminar','2001-03-02','The Role of the CIO and Information Superiority','','\"The Role of the CIO\" fits particularly well since Strassmann has recently\r\nrevisited the research done by the PIMS organization on what determines profitability.<p>\r\n\r\nStrassmann\'s recent studies of corporations with recognized reputation for IT sophistication (e.g. Motorola, Chrysler/Daimler, Xerox and EDS) show that the role of IT may come to play only if it does NOT perform, e.g. when it fails.  Otherwise, IT should be seen only as an arms race where all competitors have the identical computer technologies and therefore cannot have\r\na sustainable competitive advantage.<p>\r\n\r\n\r\nIf that is so, the role of the CIO emerges as being largely  \"political/governance\", with technology pushed back either\r\nto a CTO or, increasingly to a services provider and outsourcing  purchases.<p>\r\n\r\n\r\nThis lecture is unconventional and is contrary to much of what the usual\r\nCIO glorification magazines promote. '),(67,'','Senior Executive Club','New Canaan, CT','','Executive Briefing','2001-01-24','The Whys and the Hows of Ballistic Missile Defenses','','What constitutes the threats to national security, what are\r\nthe ballistic weapons already in possession of our potential attackers,\r\nhow ballistic weapons operate and what are the engineering problems\r\nfor our defenses are topics that will be receiving much attention\r\nin the years to come.<p>\r\n\r\nStrassmann, the former Director of Defense Information, will\r\ndiscuss  \"Defending the U.S. The Why and How of Ballistic Missile Defense.\"  In\r\na profusely illustrated lecture he will show pictures of missile launches and\r\nmissile intercepts.  The BMD budget, the inventory of missiles in hostile\r\nhands and the political aspects of existing treaties will be also discussed.\r\nThe presentation will explain why the U.S. is, at present,\r\ndefenseless against ballistic missile attacks and is likely to remain\r\nthat way for years to come.'),(68,'','InfoViDE, Warsaw, Poland','','Private resort in Poland','Executive seminar and workshop','2001-06-07','Assessment of Information Productivity and Information Technologies','<a href=\"http://www.infovide.pl/firma/wydarzenia/ik/index.html\">More Info</a>',''),(69,'','Private organization','Video conference','','Briefing','2001-02-15','Assessment of Outsourcing Options','',''),(70,'','Major government organization','Washington, D.C.','','Briefing','2001-02-27','Governance for Information Superiority','',''),(71,'','Private group','','','Briefing','2001-03-18','Special Forces Operations in WWII','',''),(72,'','Policy group','Washington, D.C.','','Briefing','2001-04-11','The Economics of Outsourcing of I.T. Services','','A discussion of the risks of outsourcing\r\na firm\'s core competencies. Case studies\r\nof a few documented outsourcing contracts\r\nthat ended up with unfavorable consequences.'),(73,'','','Washington, D.C.','','Briefing','2001-03-05','Software Defects - Gateways to Cyberterrorism','',''),(74,'','Private','','Arlington, VA','Briefing','2001-02-23','Governance Design for Information Superiority','','This presentation emphasizes the importance of making an assessment of operating issues and a quantitative evaluation of performance prior to\r\ndrafting proposals to reorganize and institution.'),(75,'','Butler Group','','Heathrow Airport, London','Keynote','2001-06-21','Transforming I.T. Costs into Profits','','The contribution of I.T. to profitability\r\nof firms is indirect, often quite subtle\r\nand always unmeasurable at the enterprise\r\nlevel of analysis.  To understand this\r\nrelationship requires a thorough understanding\r\nof the determinants of corporate profitability.<p>\r\n\r\nPerhaps the only empiric study that illuminates\r\nthis question is the research that has been\r\nconducted for over 25 years by the Strategic\r\nPlanning Institute (the PIMS research) and\r\nits follow-on research organizations.  \r\nStrassmann will describe the basis for such\r\nanalysis of corporate profitability and\r\nillustrate how the PIMS methodology \r\nwould guide the planning and budgeting\r\nof I.T. investments. '),(76,'','Butler Group','The Grand Sofitel Demure, Amsterdam, The Netherlands','Amsterdam','Keynote','2001-09-18','The New Economics of IT Management','<a href=\"http://www.butlergroup.com/events/master.asp?code=NEMERD180901\">Program</a>','Paul Strassmann will share his analysis of the radical shift that is taking place in the IT industry and in the economy at large. The approach to IT spending and the rationale for outsourcing have completely changed in the last few years, and new rules are needed. Paul will make a comprehensive analysis of the impact of this new situation and what these new rules could be.<p>\r\n\r\nThe key lessons of the classes are:<p>\r\n\r\n- coping with the failure of the software industry to match the explosion in capability of hardware and network technologies\r\n- understanding the forces at work that encourage the concentration of powers in a small group of vendors\r\n- appreciating the growing importance of information in business and the importance of what was traditionally considered an ‘overhead’ in the wealth of companies\r\n- appreciating the need to adopt a more scientific approach to management in the information age\r\n- understanding the shift in the way business services are delivered\r\n- understanding the new rules that are emerging in the way to manage IT\r\n- learning how to take steps for taking advantage of the new rules\r\n- Learning how to take the steps for taking advantage of the new rules.\r\n\r\n'),(77,'','Richmond Events','Aboard QE2','Sailing from New York','Keynoter & Conference Chairman','2001-05-16','Information Productivity in Banking','<a href=\"http://www.cioforum.com/conference/\">Registration</a>','The CIO Forum Financial Services - 2001 from May 16-19, 2001, will take place on board the QE2 sailing from New York City. The CIO Forum Financial Services - 2001 is the leading strategic IT forum for the US financial services industry. Launched in 1998, the Forum has now become a permanent feature of the IT management calendar - providing a structured arena for establishing new business contacts, real problem solving, networking with peers and debating the industry\'s hot topics and the latest innovations. Participation is by invitation only. '),(78,'','Richmond Events','Aboard QE2','Sailing from New York','Workshop','2001-05-07','The Politics of Information Management','<a href=\"http://www.cioforum.com/conference/\">Registration</a>','Based on his 35 years of experience as the computer chief for major corporations\r\nStrassmann is in a good position to lead the discussion about the  \"Political\"\r\n(e.g. \"Governance\") aspects of corporate information management.\r\nAccording to Strassmann\'s 1993 book on this subject \"...information management\r\nis the continuation of organizational politics by other means.\"  Politics, not\r\neconomics, usually shapes choices of technologies.  Politics largely\r\ndetermines whether computer projects will succeed or fail.  Politics is by far \r\nthe most frequent cause of a firings of systems executives.\r\nThe solution to political infighting is the institution of rules of governance that offer guidelines how to partition the conflicting forces.  Governance\r\noffers the means for achieving a balance between centralization and decentralization of business functions.  The techniques for resolving opposing tendencies cannot be learned from books about information technology.  Reading\r\nup about constitutional history, or attending this workshop, will most\r\nlikely be useful in learning what to do.'),(79,'','INFOWARCON 2001','Washington, D.C.','','Plenary presentation','2001-09-05','Software Defects: Gateways to Cyberterrorism','<a href=\"http://www.interpactinc.com/infowarcon.htm\">More Info</a>','Though walls, sentries, gates and locks\r\nmake a fortress more secure a faulty\r\nfoundation and poor design will\r\nalways make it penetrable.\r\n\r\nMr. Strassmann will describe why and\r\nhow existing software engineering and \r\nnetwork architectures are inherently \r\ndefective.  The blame for this\r\nsituation can be placed on vendors \r\nwho deliver software that is bloated to meet\r\nprimarily marketing needs.  The fault also\r\nrests with application designers\r\nwho deliver software of\r\nsuch complexity that it is humanly infeasible\r\nto protect it.\r\n\r\nThe solution to this situation can be found\r\nin the adoption of systems architectures of\r\nmuch greater simplicity.  This requires the placement\r\nof most of the software codes in computer utilities\r\nwhere much higher security standards\r\ncan be implemented and enforced.\r\nSince such changes would \r\ncompromise the privacy of individuals\r\nStrassmann is advocating the separation\r\nof personal from corporate computing\r\nsoftware management practices.  \r\n'),(80,'','Government Agency Strategic Planners','Montgomery, Alabama','Air University, Department of the Air Force','Briefing','2001-05-10','The Coming Revolution in Systems Affairs','',''),(81,'','','Washington, D.C.','','Private Briefing','2001-06-15','Revolution in Systems Affairs - An  Industry View','','As vendors shift from sales of equipment and software to the delivery of transaction services the process for delivery of information management functions will be changing. Large cost reductions and increased reliability of information technology will be the result, though major disruptions in the established organizations will accompany such developments.'),(82,'','Government Policy-Level Executives','Syracuse University','','Briefing','2001-08-27','Policy Guidelines for Security of Network Services','',''),(83,'','The Butler Group','Park Lane Hilton','London','Keynote','2001-09-20','The New Economics of IT Management Master Class ','<a href=\"http://www.butlergroup.com/events/master.asp?code=NEMUAD200901\">Program</a>','Paul Strassmann will share his analysis of the radical shift that is taking place in the IT industry and in the economy at large. The approach to IT spending and the rationale for outsourcing have completely changed in the last few years, and new rules are needed. Paul will make a comprehensive analysis of the impact of this new situation and what these new rules could be.<p>\r\n\r\nThe key lessons of the classes are:<p>\r\n\r\n<li>coping with the failure of the software industry to match the explosion in capability of hardware and network technologies\r\n<li>understanding the forces at work that encourage the concentration of powers in a small group of vendors\r\n<li>appreciating the growing importance of information in business and the importance of what was traditionally considered an ‘overhead’ in the wealth of companies\r\n<li>appreciating the need to adopt a more scientific approach to management in the information age\r\n<li>understanding the shift in the way business services are delivered\r\n<li>understanding the new rules that are emerging in the way to manage IT\r\n<li>learning how to take steps for taking advantage of the new rules\r\n<li>Learning how to take the steps for taking advantage of the new rules.\r\n'),(84,'','Private Briefing','','','Keynote','2002-04-05','Unconventional Threats to National Security','','Briefing to senior executives on unconventional risks that can be expected over the next 20 years.'),(85,'','Delphi Group','Marriott Rancho Las Palmas','Palm Springs, CA','Keynote','2001-10-03','Justifying Investment in Information Technology in an Era of Scarce Funding','<a href=\"http://www.delphigroup.com/events/portal-conference-2001/mandate_keynotes.htm#strassmann\">Program</a>','JUSTIFYING INVESTMENTS IN I.T.\r\nIN AN ERA OF SCARCE FUNDING\r\n\r\nThe recent levels of corporate spending for\r\nI.T. are unsustainable because I.T. has been\r\nabsorbing close to 50% all available\r\ninvestment funds.  The absence of \r\na demonstrable relationship between\r\nI.T. budgets and  corporate profitability\r\nhas also lead to increased demands to\r\ndemonstrate positive payoffs from\r\ngeneric investments in a firm\'s information\r\ninfrastructure.  \r\n\r\nMr. Strassmann will illustrate a number\r\nof techniques that could be useful when\r\nmaking a proposal for funding innovative\r\nuses of I.T. that serve general purposes, such as portals,\r\nas contrasted with readily identifiable objectives\r\nfor incremental improvements.\r\n\r\nThe talk will include a description of: 1. Information Productivity\r\nBenchmarking; 2. Strategic Portfolio Analysis;\r\n3. Functional Economic Analysis.\r\nThe emphasis of this talk will be on how to prepare for\r\nfinancial planning and budgeting reviews that\r\nnow insist on demonstrable and independently\r\nmeasurable performance measures.'),(86,'','Element K','Interent','Global','Web Broadcast','2001-09-12','The Value of Employee Knowledge Capital','','Audience participation discussion'),(87,'','','Seaview Marriott, Atlantic City, N.J.','','Private Briefing','2001-08-01','Articulating the Corporate Value of IT for a Major Oil Company','','Presentation included competitive assessment of information productivity results.'),(88,'','Columbia University Executive Program','IBM Conference Center, Palisades, NY','','Opening Keynote','2001-07-22','Global Challenge for Getting Value from I.T.','','Opening talk in course for top executives of one of the largest global insurance firms.'),(89,'','InfoWarCon 2001','Renaissance Washington Hotel','Washington, D.C.','Presentation','2001-09-06','Software Defects: Gateways to Cyber-Terrorism','','Software Defects: Gateways  to Cyberterrorism\r\n\r\nThough walls, sentries, gates and locks\r\nmake a fortress more secure a faulty\r\nfoundation and poor design will\r\nalways make it penetrable.\r\n\r\nMr. Strassmann will describe why and\r\nhow existing software engineering and \r\nnetwork architectures are inherently \r\ndefective.  The blame for this\r\nsituation can be placed on vendors \r\nwho deliver software that is bloated to meet\r\nprimarily marketing needs.  The fault also\r\nrests with application designers\r\nwho deliver software of\r\nsuch complexity that it is humanly infeasible\r\nto protect it.\r\n\r\nThe solution to this situation can be found\r\nin the adoption of systems architectures of\r\nmuch greater simplicity.  This requires the placement\r\nof most of the software codes in computer utilities\r\nwhere much higher security standards\r\ncan be implemented and enforced.\r\nSince such changes would \r\ncompromise the privacy of individuals\r\nStrassmann is advocating the separation\r\nof personal from corporate computing\r\nsoftware management practices.  \r\n'),(90,'','EuroCio Conference','Brussels','Hotel Le Plaza, 118-126 Boulevard Adolphe Max, 1000 Brussels','Keynote','2001-11-30','The Changing Role of the CIOs','<A href=\"http://www.eurocio.org/programme/conferences/index.html\">Program</a>','The keynote will address the rapidly changing roles of the\r\nCIO as principal vendors (Microsoft, IBM, Sun,\r\nH-P, Cisco and Oracle) are changing their business model\r\nfrom selling (or licensing) technology to offering\r\ncompletely integrated application services.\r\n\r\nThe Strassmann model scenario shows that at present the customer\r\nspends internally about 73% of total IT costs, with\r\nthe balance going to vendors.  The most likely\r\nscenario is that within 10-15 years the customer\r\nshares of IT spending will decline to less than\r\n40%, with vendor supplied computer services taking\r\nover most of the remaining IT costs.  This will result in drastic cuts in \r\ncorporate IT staffs.\r\n\r\nThis news may not be welcome by some CIOs\r\n- nevertheless the evidence is\r\nnow overwhelming that the era of large\r\nscale growth of corporate IT staffs is\r\nover as more efficient methods of\r\nsoftware and communication management\r\npractices become available.  If the Strassmann scenario\r\nis reasonably close to what the future\r\nwill bring about, then the \r\nstaffing and organization of the \r\ncorporate IT function will result in \r\na far-reaching re-examination of \r\nmissions an responsibilities.\r\n\r\nThis de-emphasis on managing technology\r\nwill finally allow the CIO to become\r\nwhat has always been the mission:\r\nthe rationalization of Information Management\r\ninstead of over-emphasis on keeping hardware\r\nand software functioning effectively.\r\n\r\nThe coming changes will enlarge the\r\nroles of the CIO, not diminish them!'),(91,'','Private','','','Briefing','2001-12-06','Transformation of Computing from Computer to Network-Centric','','A private briefing on the shifts in IT budgets\r\nto services.'),(92,'','PeopleSoft and Hewlett-Packard','London, UK','Queen Elizabeth II Exhibition Hall - Westminster','Keynote','2002-01-31','Collaborative Commerce and Return on Investment','<a href=\"http://www.collaborativecommerce.co.uk/programme.cfm\">Program</a>','Paul Strassmann, renowned as a former cost-cutting CIO at the US Dept. of Defence, has written several books about IT return on investment. Here he reveals important new research into the RoI from collaborative commerce technologies '),(93,'','Energy Information Technology Conference','New Orleans, LA','Hyatt Regency','Keynote','2002-01-14','Justifying I.T. Spending in an Era of Scarce Funding','<A href=\"http://www.energyitexpo.com/conf.html\">Registration</a>','Mr. Strassmann will demonstrate how new analytic \r\ntechniques could be applied in justifying \r\nIT investments. <p>\r\n\r\nIt is probable that during their tenure each IT executive from the electric and gas utility industry will be confronted with the challenge to prove that they contribute to superior productivity results. Mr. Strassmann has analyzed the Information Productivity&reg; of over 100 US electric and gas utility firms. He found that a number of firms could be vulnerable to outsourcing their IT operations because of substandard performance. The purpose of his presentation will be to explain how IT executives should measure and evaluate their productivity in terms that are relevant to financial executives as well to any regulatory inquiries.\r\n'),(94,'','Institute for Defense Analyses','2002 Defense Economics Conference','Arlington, VA','Presentation','2002-02-14','Measuring the Transaction Productivity of Organizations','<a href=\"http://www.economics.osd.mil/seventh.html\">Details</a>','The Government Performance Results Act of 1993 requires Departments and Agencies to describe the means for verifying and validate measured values. This calls for the application of \"Outcome measures\" to asssess the results of an activity as compared with its intended purposes. <p>\r\n\r\nStrassmann\'s remarks will address the question of Agency productivity measurement by focusing on the ratio of cost of goods to the costs of the total value-chain transactions. Examples from General Motors, K-Mart and Wal-Mart will be used to illustrate the application of the proposed measures. '),(95,'','SAIC','SAIC','La Jolla, CA','Seminar','2002-01-11','Info Management in Energy Firms','',''),(96,'','U of Virginia, McIntyre School of Business','University of Virginia','Charlottesville, VA','Seminar','2002-02-15','Justification of IT Spending','',''),(97,'','Gartner Group','IT Asset Management and TCO Summit 2002','Orlando, FL','Keynote','2002-06-05','Justification of IT Spending','<a href=\"http://www4.gartner.com/2_events/conferences/bam10/bam10.jsp\">Registration</a>','In this presentation Strassmann will \"play act\" the preparation\r\nof a presentation to the Executive Committee of\r\na firm that has applied the published industry\r\n&lt;IT as % of Revenue Ratio&gt; to suggest a\r\n10% cut in IT spending.  The purpose of\r\nmy talk will be  to demonstrate, in a step-wise sequence,\r\nhow one should approach such a challenge.<p>\r\n\r\nThe talk will illustrate how the structure of\r\na corporation shapes IT spending and how it determines\r\nthe TCO of information management.  The\r\ntalk will highlight how one should explain\r\nthe TCO in comparison\r\nwith superior as well as inferior competitors.  '),(98,'','Government/Industry Consortium','New Haven, CT','','Private Briefing','2002-03-07','War-gaming Information Terrorist Threats','',''),(99,'','Butler Group','','Amsterdam','Keynote','2002-04-22','Justifying IT Spending in an Era of Scarce Funding','','The objective of this Master Class is to equip an IT executive with techniques and methods how to respond to inquiries about the value of IT.  Contemporary survey results of CEOs, CFOs and CIOs confirm that reviews of IT will be subjected to especially skeptical examinations in the years to come. Session 1 will deal with reviews of business cases for making investments in individual projects.  Such examinations usually take place at the Departmental level.\r\nSession 2 will address how IT affects the viability of individual businesses and will concentrate on the application of Information Productivity measures.  Such examinations are conducted mostly during Operating budget reviews.\r\nSession 3 will examine the strategic impacts of information technologies and how they affect the Knowledge Capital as well as risks in competitive confrontations in the 21st century.  These matters are of concern at the Board of Directors level and arise during major re-examinations of enterprise strategies.\r\n  '),(100,'','Butler Group','','Stockholm','Keynote','2002-04-24','Justifying IT Spending in an Era of Scarce Funding','','The objective of this Master Class is to equip an IT executive with techniques and methods how to respond to inquiries about the value of IT.  Contemporary survey results of CEOs, CFOs and CIOs confirm that reviews of IT will be subjected to especially skeptical examinations in the years to come.  Session 1 will deal with reviews of business cases for making investments in individual projects.  Such examinations usually take place at the Departmental level.\r\nSession 2 will address how IT affects the viability of individual businesses and will concentrate on the application of Information Productivity measures.  Such examinations are conducted mostly during Operating budget reviews.\r\nSession 3 will examine the strategic impacts of information technologies and how they affect the Knowledge Capital as well as risks in competitive confrontations in the 21st century.  These matters are of concern at the Board of Directors level and arise during major re-examinations of enterprise strategies.'),(101,'','Butler Group','London','','Keynote','2002-04-25','Justifying IT Spending in an Era of Scarce Funding','','The objective of this Master Class is to equip an IT executive with techniques and methods how to respond to inquiries about the value of IT.  Contemporary survey results of CEOs, CFOs and CIOs confirm that reviews of IT will be subjected to especially skeptical examinations in the years to come.  Session 1 will deal with reviews of business cases for making investments in individual projects.  Such examinations usually take place at the Departmental level.\r\nSession 2 will address how IT affects the viability of individual businesses and will concentrate on the application of Information Productivity measures.  Such examinations are conducted mostly during Operating budget reviews.\r\nSession 3 will examine the strategic impacts of information technologies and how they affect the Knowledge Capital as well as risks in competitive confrontations in the 21st century.  These matters are of concern at the Board of Directors level and arise during major re-examinations of enterprise strategies.\r\n'),(102,'','Private','','','Keynote','2002-04-05','The History and Organization of Special Forces ','',''),(103,'','NASA','Information Science &amp; Technology Colloquium Series','Goddard Space Flight Center, Greenbelt, MD','Colloquium','2002-09-18','Information Productivity: A Metric for the Information Economy','<a href=\"http://isandtcolloq.gsfc.nasa.gov/fall2002/speakers/strassmann.html\">NASA</a>','Mr. Paul Strassmann, will talk about Information Productivity: A Metric for the Information Economy. Mr. Strassmann will describe his work on measuring the effectiveness of information technology investments starting with initial findings in 1979, pilot research from 1982-1985, institutional resistance to measuring the total costs of information resources and gradual acceptance of the metric. The presentation will conclude with a demonstration of just released software that relates information productivity to conventional financial accounting practices.\r\n'),(104,'','','EuroCIO 2002','Brussels','Keynote','2002-12-05','Emerging Top CIO Pains','<a href=\"http://www.eurocio.org\">Euro CIO</a>',''),(105,'','AFCEA','Washington Chapter Luncheon','Arlington, VA','Keynote Address','2003-03-19','Power Politics of the CIO','<a href=\"http://www.washdcafcea.org/\">AFCEA</a> | <a href=\"http://www.strassmann.com/pubs/fed/AFCEA-2003.html\">Lecture notes</a> | <a href=\"http://www.strassmann.com/talks/files/2003-03-19.pdf\">Announcement</a>','Paul Strassmann will be the guest speaker at our March 19 luncheon, where he will share his thoughts on the power politics of the Chief Information Officer (CIO). In his lively speech and the ensuing question/answer period he will demonstrate that a successful CIO must manage information technology as a continuation of bureaucratic power politics. Topics for discussion include:\r\n\r\n<li>The limitations of a Technology CIO\r\n<li>The importance of an Information Management CIO\r\n<li>The roles of an Information Strategy CIO\r\n<li>The shift of the CIO power base from computing to telecommunication\r\n<li>CIO power that must not be outsourced'),(106,'','General Services Administration (GSA)','FTS 2003 Network Services Conference','Orlando, FL','Executive panel','2003-04-01','The Future of Federal Network Services','<a href=\"http://www.gsa-fts.com/\">GSA-FTS</a> | <a href=\"http://www.strassmann.com/pubs/fed/fts-2003.html\">Talk</a>',''),(107,'','Federal Holocaust Remembrance Committee','Holocaust Days of Remembrance Program','Lincoln Theater, Washington DC','Emcee','2003-05-01','10th Annual Federal Observance','<a href=\"http://holocaustremembrance.org/\">holocaustremembrance.org</a>',''),(108,'','IDC','The European IT Forum 2003','Paris','Keynote','2003-09-29','Aligning IT Projects for Value','<a href=\"http://emea.idc.com/itforum03\">Registration</a>','Mr. Strassmann will describe three approaches \r\nfor achieving favorable economic returns from I.T. and \r\nhow to align I.T.  with the goals of an organization. <p>\r\n\r\nThe first approach addresses the management of technologies;  the second \r\ndeals with  the productivity of administrative personnel;  the third covers competitive gains.  <p>\r\n\r\nThe talk will concentrate on how information technology proposals \r\nought to be structured to settle conflicts about investment priorities \r\nand for getting executive attention focused on potential economic gains. <p>\r\n\r\nLarge scale investments in industrial machinery lagged until General Motors pioneered the adoption of formal methods of financial analysis and budgetary planning in the early 1920\'s.<p>\r\n\r\nWe have just come the end of a 50-year period of euphoric growth in the adoption of computers but without a disciplined approach to the evaluation of prospective payoffs.  The pervasive effects of information technology investments make it now necessary to integrate such expenditures with the existing financial disciplines.<p>\r\n\r\nMr. Strassmann is unanimously recognised as the leading worldwide authority in the area of IT investment justification. He will explain what will fail and recommend what will succeed when asking for scarce funding.'),(109,'','Gartner','Application Development Summit','Los Angeles','Keynote','2003-09-22','The #1 CIO Issue:  How to Explain and Justify the I.T. Budget','<a href=\"http://www.gartner.com/2_events/conferences/2003/ad5/ad5.jsp\">Registration</a> | \r\n<a href=\"http://www.strassmann.com/pubs/gartner/howto-budgets.pdf\">Slides</a>\r\n<font size=-1>(4MB pdf)</font>','Last year, corporations worldwide spent over $2 trillion on information technology. Half of that was spent by US corporations alone. But did they get their money\'s worth? How can you really measure white-collar productivity? What are the real causes of success and failure in corporate information management?<p>\r\n\r\nDrawing on his years as the head of information systems at Kraft Foods, Xerox, the US Department of Defense, and NASA, Paul Strassmann is a renowned authority on IT productivity and return on investment - issues that have come to dominate the agenda of many organizations today. '),(110,'','Georgia State University','I/S Executive Roundtable','Georgia State University','Lecture','2003-09-18','Explaining to your CFO why IT <u>does</u> matter','','The May issue of the Harvard Business Review carried a \r\nan article by one of its Editors with the provocative title \r\n\"IT Does not Matter\".  The author declared that \r\ninformation technology has become strategically irrelevant. \r\nConsequently the article recommended the adoption of the following policies: <p>\r\n\r\nA. Cut the IT budgets; <br>\r\nB. Do not invest in information-technology innovations; <br>\r\nC. Invest only after others have succeeded – follow not lead; <br>\r\nD. Delay IT investments because prices are dropping and everything will be less expensive later; <br>\r\n\r\nE. Refocus from seeking opportunities to managing vulnerabilities and risks; <br>\r\n\r\nF. Disregard vendors’ innovative offerings because they are suspect for seeking added revenues; <br>\r\n\r\nG. Delay innovation as the preferred way for cutting IT costs. <br>\r\n<p>\r\n\r\nStrassmann responded to each of the HBR recommendations in a letter \r\ncited in publications such as Fortune and The New York Times. \r\nBecause the HBR article is likely to be used as guidance \r\nin IT budget reviews for 2004 and 2005, Strassmann will discuss \r\nhow and why the arguments presented in the HBR article \r\nhave little merit.  Strassmann will also offer specific recommendations \r\nhow CIOs should get ready to demonstrate IT relevance in an \r\nera wherein cutbacks in spending for information technologies have \r\nbecome one of the preferred ways how to improve financial \r\nperformance.<p> \r\n\r\n\r\nStrassmann has served as CIO since 1961 for General Foods, \r\nKraft, Xerox, the Department of Defense and NASA. He is \r\nauthor of five books and hundreds of articles about the \r\neconomics of computer investments.  For more information \r\nconsult <www.strassmann.com> and biographical information \r\non <http://www.strassmann.com/bio.html> \r\n'),(111,'','New Canaan Historical Society','','New Canaan, CT','Lecture','2003-09-15','The Written Word from Cave Drawings to Interstellar Communication','','Our civilization has been steadily accumulating wealth because we have acquired\r\nthe capacity to keep adding to the stores of shared knowledge.  Though our\r\norigins can be traced back for  400,000 years, it was the\r\ninvention of writing, about 5,000 years ago, that propelled much of the\r\nprogress in politics, religion, law and technology.<p>\r\n\r\nUnderstanding how the evolution of the written word relates to the\r\nprogress in human culture is now necessary for comprehending\r\nthe consequences of the current  explosion in global communications.<p>\r\n\r\nMr. Strassmann will accompany his talk with illustrated examples that span\r\n10,000 years of recored communications.  This will include cave drawings,\r\nprecursors of writing, the evolution of the alphabet and how\r\nprinting as well as electronic transmissions are causing revolutionary\r\nchanges in organizations.  His talk will also use copies of exhibits from the collection\r\nof written communications, still on display in the lobby of the Xerox HQ in\r\nStamford. He will also show a print of signals from Project SETI, now searching\r\nfor communications from outer space, as well as pictures of NASA\r\nextra-terrestial probes. An original sheep-skin page from Gutenberg\'s printing shop\r\nwill be also on display.<p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<b>Biography:</b><br>\r\nWhen the new Xerox HQ was originally planned in 1977, Strassmann\r\nvolunteered to assemble a collection of historical examples  that would serve\r\nas a testimonial to the contributions of xerography towards the advancement of shared\r\nknowledge.  Although his background is technical (MIT, 1955), he has found that\r\nhis interest in the history of communication has been helpful in steering\r\nthe adoption of computers under rapidly changing circumstances.<p>\r\n\r\n Since 1961 he has served as Chief Computer executive for General Foods, Kraft,\r\nXerox, Department of Defense and NASA.  Strassmann, a New Canaan\r\nresident and publisher of books since 1975, is a frequent lecturer on the historical changes brought\r\nabout by information technologies.  His early predictions that the \"paperless office\"\r\nwill never happen received global attention from bibliophiles and archivists.\r\n\r\n'),(112,'','National Security Studies','','Syracuse, New York','Lecture','2003-10-07','Structure and Management of Information Technologies in the Federal Government','<a href=\"http://www.nss.edu/\">National Security Studies</a>','\r\n\r\n'),(113,'','Butler Group','Information Economics Summit','Hampshire, UK','Keynote','2004-06-07','Unlocking the Secrets of Information Economics','<a href=\"http://www.strassmann.com/talks/files/2004-06-IES.pdf\">Conference brochure</a> (3.4MB pdf)','<li> Structure of a firm’s costs of information and how they are related to IT \r\n<li> Measuring information productivity \r\n<li> Use of information productivity and measures of transaction cost \r\neffectiveness \r\n<li> The growing importance of transaction costs in global competition\r\n<li> Opportunity for delegates to apply methodology to their own organizations\r\n<p>\r\n<li> Outsourcing &amp; Offshoring Case Studies'),(114,'','Center for the Management of Information Technology','Enterprise Systems Integration','University of Virginia','Keynote','2004-03-05','Politics of IT Architecture','<a href=\"http://www.commerce.virginia.edu/cmit/activities/a_march04.htm\">Agenda</a>','This program will explore the possibilities and challenges of integrating information systems both within and across enterprises. The morning will feature presentations by two individuals that have exceptional experience in this area. First, Steve Cooper, CIO of the Department of Homeland Security, will describe the politics and process of integrating homeland security information across numerous databases and enterprises. <P>\r\n\r\nPaul Strassmann, former CIO of the Department of Defense, NASA, and Xerox Corporation, will then discuss the “politics of IT architecture,” including managing interdependencies, bureaucracies, and economic issues. Implications for enterprise and national security will also be addressed. The afternoon will include panelists from diverse organizations who will share their current challenges in the drive toward integrating enterprise systems'),(115,'','IDC Italia','CIO Conference 2005','Milan','Keynote','2005-05-09','Managing Outsourcing: The CIO Challenge for the Next Decade','<a href=\"http://www.idc.com/italy/events/cio05/cio05.jsp\">Conference</a> | \r\n<a href=\"http://www.strassmann.com/talks/files/2005-5-milan.pdf\">Agenda</a> |\r\n<a href=\"http://www.strassmann.com/blog/cioidc/\">Lecture Blog</a>','Increasing technical complexity in developing firm-specific\r\napplications, rising labor costs for software maintenance and rapid\r\nobsolescence of information technology favor the shifting of\r\ninternal IT costs to externally purchased services.<p>\r\n\r\nThe 1-to-5 ratio of external to internal IT costs reflecting the 1990\'s allocation of IT budgets will now transform to a 3-to-1 ratio by the end of 2010.<p>\r\n\r\nThe increased emphasis on outsourcing will be also illustrated by\r\na number of examples showing that this is not a unique IT trend\r\nbut a reflection of global competitive trends seeking to improve\r\ninformation productivity by all available means. The consequences\r\non the organization, leadership skills and the management of IT will\r\nbe far reaching. Mr. Strassmann expects that systems integration,\r\nproject management and technology migration planning will now\r\nemerge as the main challenges that the CIOs will need to master.\r\n'),(116,'','George Mason University','','Fairfax, VA','Lecture','2005-10-03','The DoD CIO Charter: A Template for IT Governance?','<a href=\"http://www.strassmann.com/pubs/multichannel/2005-10-google.pdf\">Slides</a>','A May 2, 2005 DoD Directive has far reaching implications in assigning to the DoD CIO with new responsibilities.  Mr. Strassmann\'s lecture will interpret the significance of the new roles'),(117,'','George Mason University','','Fairfax, VA','Lecture','2005-12-05','Google: A Model for the Systems Architecture of the Future','<a href=\"http://www.strassmann.com/pubs/gmu/LectureV4.pdf\">Slides</a> |\r\n<a href=\"http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=6682253938984655269\">Video</a>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','<p>Focus on Integration: The Future of Government Systems</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The proliferation of application-specific infrastructures, the redundancies in data definitions and the escalating support costs have delivered systems that are not affordable.  Mr. Strassmann will show why systems management will be shifting focus from systems development to systems integration.</P>'),(118,'','George Mason University','','Fairfax, VA','Lecture','2006-03-06','Is Outsourcing Profitable?','<a href=\"http://www.strassmann.com/pubs/gmu/Lecture-3.pdf\">Poster</a> |\r\n<a href=\"http://www.strassmann.com/pubs/gmu/OutsourcingV6.pdf\">Slides</a> |\r\n<a href=\"http://video.google.com/videoplay?docid=9212234366223965964\">Video</a>','<p>The history of U.S. industrial firms for the last 20 years can \r\nbe characterized by an increasing dependency on outsourcing \r\nto suppliers, subcontractors or even to customers.  This phenomenon \r\nhas been explained on the assumption that specialists, or lower \r\ncost vendors, could deliver contributions to the cost of goods at \r\na discount.  Proponents of outsourcing were also relying on \r\ninformation technologies to lower the administrative as well as \r\ncoordination costs to manage the increased complexity in all \r\ntransactions.  However, despite the logic that would favor \r\noutsourcing, little evidence has been produced to support \r\noutsourcing as a general industrial policy. </p>\r\n \r\n<p>In this lecture Prof. Strassmann will show results of his studies over the last ten years which have \r\ndemonstrated that outsourcing does not consistently deliver lower costs and increased \r\nprofitability.  This lecture will be illustrated by the record of General Motors who have increased \r\nthe amounts of outsourcing from 58.8% in 1986 to 75% in 2004 while experiencing a steady \r\ndegradation in profitability as well as a severe decline in its Knowledge Capital per employee.  \r\nWhile the number of General Motors employees was declining, the ratio of transaction costs to \r\nvalue-added was rising which raises the question whether GM\'s outsourcing of I.T. was effective. </P>\r\n \r\n<p>The presence of the perverse effects of outsourcing have been now detected for a large number \r\nof U.S. industrial firms.  Prof. Strassmann has concluded that the key in making decisions \r\nabout achieving cost reductions through outsourcing is to also consider the effects on the \r\nconsequential gains or losses in a firm’s Knowledge Capital. His findings will be supported by \r\nfinancial data from over 500 U.S. industrial firms. </P>'),(119,'','George Mason University','','Fairfax, VA','Lecture','2006-04-17','How Much is An Employee Worth?','<a href=\"http://www.strassmann.com/pubs/gmu/Lecture4.pdf\">Poster</a> |\r\n<a href=\"http://www.strassmann.com/pubs/gmu/2006-4-17-slides.pdf\">Slides</a>\r\n','<p>Economists have long viewed compensation as an employee’s worth. If an\r\nemployee receives $100,000 a year, that’s what he’s worth.\r\nProf. Strassmann can demonstrate that such reasoning is a fallacy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This lecture will present arguments that one must turn to the competitive\r\nmarketplace to determine the worth of an employee. Chief information\r\nofficers should understand how to calculate such worth before they move to\r\ncut information technology costs. I.T, after all, is a people-to-knowledge\r\nvalue enabler. Because the value of knowledge is often a large multiple of\r\nwhat the accountants report as costs, even small improvements in the ratio\r\nof knowledge to costs can result in enormous gains.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Students can learn how to quantify the value of knowledge within an entire company by using a straight-forward formula: subtract a company’s shareholder equity, or financial value, from its market capitalization, or market value, to come up with what is a company’s “knowledge value.”</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Strassmann will also explain how such a number can be obtained by applying his trademarked \"Knowledge Capital\" equation. In the case of the not-for-profit public sector, a comparative calculation can be also performed. Improvements in the value of knowledge can result in value appreciation whereas cost reductions may accomplish that only indirectly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Only knowledgeable humans — with or without effective I.T. — can deliver productivity, competitive advantages or whatever is necessary to help businesses in thriving. The lecture will include a table of U.S. firms where employees are worth a large multiple of what they are paid.</p>'),(120,'','','Transformation and Innovation Conference','Washington, DC','Keynote','2006-05-22','Business Data Transformation','<a href=\"http://www.transformationandinnovation.com/\">Conference</a> |\r\n<a href=\"http://www.strassmann.com/pubs/gmu/2006-05-22.pdf\">Slides</a>',''),(121,'','','European CIOs','','Keynote','2006-04-28','Governance & Alignment In the Era of Business Transformation','<a href=\"http://www.strassmann.com/pubs/talks/2006-4-28-governance.pdf\">Slides</a>',''),(122,'','Pulver Media','IP4IT','Las Vegas','Keynote','2005-11-12','The Next IT Tsunami','<a href=\"ip4it.com\">Conference site</a> <a href=\"http://www.strassmann.com/pubs/talks/2005-11-ip4it.mp3\">Podcast</a> <a href=\"http://www.strassmann.com/pubs/talks/IP4ITV3.ppt\">Slides</a>','');
